(1058, 1, '2016-01-19 12:03:34', '2016-01-19 12:03:34', '<strong>After reading this article you will know</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>how to decrease the potential of shoulder injury </strong></li>\n	<li><strong>what packing your shoulders means</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>the benefits of focusing on perfect form</strong></li>\n</ul>\nYour shoulders are one of the most mobile joints in your body. The high mobility factor increases also the potential for injury. To prevent injury effectively you have to know about isolating your shoulders. There are four positions you should keep in mind during your workouts for certain exercises. The terminologies for the four positions are protraction and retraction as well as depression and elevation. We covered the terms in more detail on our website, here. But to make it short protraction and retraction is known as moving your scapulae outwards and towards each other, while depression and elevation is known as moving your scapulae down and up.\n\nIn Ykings workouts you will come across these terms quite frequently and when we refer to packing your shoulders it means that you should depress your scapulae or pushing your shoulders down. Some people will hear the term packing the shoulder and immediately think of immobilizing the shoulder. This is not what we mean. Packing the shoulder means motor control over a range of motion that isolates specific injury prone movements. So, make use of depression in exercises that include dipping or static holds such as the L-Sit.\n\nAnother important routine to further increase your mobility are exercises such as the shoulder dislocate. These mobility exercises are often overlooked, but at Ykings we have integrated several exercises in each warmup to ensure you focus on shoulder health, strength and mobility. Most of people who work out have strength and mobility in specific ranges of motion. Motions and movements in the range of the front body to overhead such as pushups, handstands, rows, pullups are well developed, however what about your backside? Starting out with working out at the bar and rings more, you might belong to the high percentage of people who lack behind the body to overhead mobility. So integrate different mobility enhancing exercises in your routine and you will develop and evolve faster.\n\nWhat do you do for more mobility in your joints? What are your best mobility exercises for shoulders, hips and legs? Please leave a comment and subscribe to our mailing list to get more awesome information.\n\nPS: In one of our next articles we will cover the benefits of stretching after each workout.\n\nYkings is a smartphone application that focuses on your overall mobility and flexibility to perform epic moves. In our personalized workout plans Ykings diligently helps you on every workout day to focus effectively to increase your range of motion.\n\n&nbsp;', 'What packing your shoulders actually means', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-packing-your-shoulders-actually-means', '', '', '2016-01-19 12:03:34', '2016-01-19 12:03:34', '', 0, 'http://ykings.com/?p=1058', 0, 'post', '', 1),
