(1133, 1, '2016-02-21 12:34:18', '2016-02-21 12:34:18', 'After reading this article you will know\n<ul>\n	<li>why learning skills is a matter of decision making</li>\n	<li>three approaches to make time when learning skills</li>\n	<li>why you need a good structure before utilizing your time</li>\n</ul>\nWe get often asked how somebody can make time to learn a specific skill when one has a family and a full time job. The first thing to understand is that working out is a decision, so is learning. In the case of skills and movement training, it is a deliberate decision to 1) learn more things in a structured way and 2) strive for personal goals. The rest is a matter of scheduling, finding or making time to work out.\n\nLet’s say you have your goals and you are ready to re-organize your lifestyle towards training. How could you start to think about making time for workouts? We want to introduce you today into three scheduling strategies that can help you in this process 1) post-workout effort 2) double dipping and 3) dedicated skills training.\n\n<u>Approach #1 – Post workout effort</u>\n\nThe most useful strategy is to do some fundamentals and basics every time you work out. If you engage in some extra work every day the numbers sum up significantly over time. Imagine putting an extra 10 minutes every time you work out. Assuming you do three workouts per week that’s 1,560 minutes or roughly 26 hours a year. As you are physically limited to do a couple hours of straight strength training you have to think about putting in extra minutes here and there. Spending an extra 26 hours on your body awareness, mobility or flexibility over the course of the year is well spent. So don’t just finish the workout but also put some extra time afterwards in the things that matter to you. Embrace the little things on the way to bigger goals. Regarding developing your skills, a structured process to address your training in the right manner such as the progression formula will improve your body effectively. Therefore the post workout effort is a powerful tool you should implement if you are serious about your skills in the long term.\n\n<u>Approach #2 – Double - dipping</u>\n\nWe like the idea of learning new skills, trying new moves, engage in new exercises while working on your conditioning and endurance. What is the point of just getting fitter if you could add a real purpose to your training using the same time slot for both? Make your time slot a win-win. Double dipping is not really a strategy but shows the usefulness of the Ykings training concept. Again a structured approach and the discipline to execute is the key to success. You will be surprised how many people are just overwhelmed with the options calisthenics related sports have to offer and get dragged away by it – not making the process they could make. Hence a good structure and an upright focus on your training are the first things to manage. Double-dipping won’t work when you try to work efficiently on the wrong things. What we call double –dipping is the approach of learning a new skill while you work out. Integrate a good portion of your learning time into your workout time slots and you will see that a deliberate effort will help you to evolve your skill set and learn new skills in a much faster pace. Get two things done in a single time slot.\n\n<u>Approach #3 – Dedicated skills training</u>\n\nThe third approach is to cancel some of your other commitments and deliberately devote time to learning. Clear your mind, clear your agenda and think about this as an investment of time in a better future you. As in business, if you invest you need to get good value out of it. Same applies in your training, because you don’t have the time to learn inefficiently from anyone less than the best and with full dedication and focus. Invest some of your valuable time to get the same learning done in substantially less time just by pure dedication and focus. You are in control. Implement a new habit in your life, e.g. do a warmup session and dedicated skills training every Saturday morning before breakfast or add a 20 minute time slot every Thursday after your workout. Schedule it in your calendar and devote the time. You can’t lose, it is for you anyways. Just remember, what doesn’t get scheduled doesn’t get done.\n\nHave more ideas on how to make time for training? Let us know, leave a comment.\n\n<strong><em>Ykings is a full body training concept that teaches elite skills and epic body moves from disciplines such as competitive gymnastics &amp; calisthenics. Get involved in the training concept that integrate not only your skill level in your workouts but structures your training so that you can evolve and progress while getting in shape. Join the Ykings family and get guided step by step with perfect tailored workout plans.</em></strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'The simple rules of making time to learn specific skills', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-simple-rules-of-making-time-to-learn-specific-skills', '', '', '2016-02-21 12:34:18', '2016-02-21 12:34:18', '', 0, 'http://ykings.com/?p=1133', 0, 'post', '', 0),
