(1194, 1, '2016-04-06 12:54:44', '2016-04-06 12:54:44', '<strong>Workout Guidelines</strong>\n\n<u>Repetitions &amp; quality form</u>\n\nAt Ykings we are not competing against time, so don’t rush it. Take considerable time to perform each repetition with quality form. Make sure you do each movement slowly and controlled. The slower and controlled you can do one repetition the stronger you will get. Watch the video tutorials for the correct range of motion and continuously work on your form. Work through our pro tips and get a spotter to assist you when trying new moves.\n\n<u>Rest days</u>\n\nRest days are your time to grow. We recommend taking sufficient time between workout days to rest your muscles and regenerate. If you feel muscle soreness then rest and rather do a good stretching or HIIT run session the next day. The better you are rested, the faster you will progress. Engage in the Ykings journey in a healthy fashion to enjoy all benefits in the long-term.\n\n<u>Breaks</u>\n\nYkings workouts &amp; exercises are demanding. Please take breaks when you need them to regain power and your breath. Aim for lesser and shorter breaks as you progress to plateau your strength and endurance. Challenge yourself to grow mentally and physically with us. Be advised to pay attention to your body signals, don’t play through pain. Make sure you read our health and safety guidelines to be safe.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><u>Health / Safety</u></strong>\n\n<strong>Some of our exercises include dynamic components and complex movements. With the complexity of routines, the risk of potential injury increases. Injuries most commonly occur in the ankles, feet, lower back, knees, wrists, and hands, often from overuse or simple stress. Injuries are rarely severe, but if left untreated they can lead to chronic pain and bone fractures. Therefore be well-rested, warmed up and always work out with quality form.</strong>\n\n<strong>If you notice symptoms or serious pain it is required to see your doctor and follow instructions for treatment and recovery. Take body signals that go beyond muscle soreness as an absolute serious warning signal!</strong>\n\n<strong>Your health and safety are our main priority and it should be yours too. Please follow proper training guidelines like in our video tutorials, use safe equipment, and work on complex skills with care. Strive for progress, be consistent and don’t risk an injury.</strong>\n\n<strong><u>Please inform yourself about cases that require the consultation of a professional. If in doubt to whether start or continue Ykings workouts please go and seek medical advice.</u></strong>\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n<strong>Your Workout Plan</strong>\n\n<u>Warmup &amp; Stretching</u>\n\nWarmups are an essential part of any Ykings workout session. Start each workout session with a good warmup routine that mobilizes your joints and gets your blood flowing. A good warmup will also support you to improve your flexibility and mobility. Warm up muscles with light aerobic exercise, such as jumping jacks, squat jumps or running in place, before beginning training or any new activities.\n\nStretching is important to enable your body to new movement and mobility patterns. Ykings recommends closing each workout session with a strict stretching regimen to shorten your rest period, avoid injury and develop a beneficial post-workout habit.\n\n<u>Fundamentals</u>\n\nFundamentals are a substantial pre-workout routine to build your muscle memory on specific moves, get you flexible and prepare your muscles for the upcoming tasks. Fundamentals have changing routines considering your personal goals and are the optimal preparation to have a great workout.\n\n<u>Skills &amp; progressions</u>\n\nRevisit the skills area from time to time and activate progressions that you want to have integrated in your workout weeks. Each activated progression will increase the workout variety of your training and bring essential parts of each skill together. You will know when to move on to the next progression, just listen to your body. The rule of thumb is to progress every four to five weeks, assuming you workout at least three times a week. The fastest progress is achieved with consistent quality work. However, be well rested and don’t get hurt.\n\n<u>Exercise types</u>\n\nYkings includes a high variety of exercises which are separated in three types.\n<ol>\n	<li><strong>Standard exercises</strong>. Achieve the rep count as laid out for these exercises. Split them up in multiple sets early on, but challenge yourself over time performing them in a single attempt.</li>\n	<li><strong>Static holds exercises</strong>. Exercises with a static hold icon will challenge your endurance &amp; strength. Try to get and endure the static holds with a minimum of pauses. Aim for the full static hold in total seconds as you progress.</li>\n	<li><strong>Endurance exercises</strong>. These exercises have a countdown timer. In contrast to static hold exercises these exercises don’t need much time to get into the hold position and start immediately after you start the exercise. Attempt to endure the exercise without breaks until the time is up.</li>\n</ol>\n<u>Workout types</u>\n\nYour workout weeks consist of several workout types such as HIIT-strength workouts, pure strength workouts, single exercises and HIIT runs. Diligently working through those workouts will optimize the efficacy of your training towards your personal goals.\n<ol>\n	<li><strong>Strength workouts</strong> - Use strength workouts to work on your form and your strength. Don’t rush while you exercise, however try to minimize your breaks between two exercises. Perform each repetition slowly and controlled for maximum results.</li>\n	<li><strong>HIIT-strength workouts</strong> - These workouts include cardio components to trigger endurance stimuli. Try to perform the whole workout without resting between exercises. Never compromise on form, even if you fight for a better time.</li>\n	<li><strong>HIIT runs</strong> - You want those six pack abs and want to look well trained and ripped. Your solution is HIIT runs. You will find them in your workout plan to increase your overall endurance and boost your metabolism. Don’t skip them if you are hunting your six pack abs.</li>\n	<li><strong>Skill raids </strong>– Skill raids are extra workout sessions which address essential muscles to get your raid done and get you closer to the skills you want to learn first. Skill raids are special and demanding workouts that can only be accessed by having the coach.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong>Progression Formula Feedback</strong>\n\n<u>Workout days</u>\n\nQuality over quantity is our simple rule for setting your workout days. Start with low numbers in the beginning, we recommend a minimum of two up to three workout days for the first couple weeks. As you progress you can intensify your experience, however don’t be overambitious but patient.\n\n<u>Limitations</u>\n\nLet the coach know when you have teared muscles or other severe limitations. We will give your affected muscles a break and challenge you in other ways. Please always look out for your health and safety and listen to the signals your body sends you. Bring the patience to work through progressions consistently and don’t move up the ladder to fast. Be aware that setting limitations significantly harms your weekly Ykings experience as you will not be able to have the full variety to progress at used speed.\n\n<u>Intensity</u>\n\nYour intensity depends on your feedback at the end of the week. The first weeks will be tough and we recommend doing less intense workout weeks with a max of three workouts per week in the beginning. Let your body adjust in a healthy way to the pace and workload of Ykings workouts.\n\n<u>Lean, athletic, strong</u>\n\nYkings workouts have three different focus tracks. Each of them includes another level of workout composition to challenge you according to your goals.\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Lean:</strong> In accordance to build strength this track focuses on strength endurance and we recommend starting it if you are a beginner and if you intend to get in shape first.</li>\n	<li><strong>Athletic:</strong> This focus track focuses on explosive strength and power. If you are an advanced athlete and just want to push for the next level, this track is for you.</li>\n	<li><strong>Strong: </strong>Strong focuses on absolute strength and provides the perfect layout to raid your skill successfully.</li>\n</ul>\nMix and vary each focus track in your workout plan to set different training stimuli. Try it out and find the track that suits you most.', 'Coach Philosophy', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'coach-philosophy', '', '', '2016-04-06 12:54:44', '2016-04-06 12:54:44', '', 0, 'http://ykings.com/?page_id=1194', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(1199, 1, '2016-04-15 05:38:18', '2016-04-15 05:38:18', 'After reading this article you will know\n<ul>\n	<li>what makes the pullup an essential exercise</li>\n	<li>why you should aim for perfect form and technique</li>\n	<li>which variations and progressions will help your development</li>\n</ul>\nOne of the most popular exercises in bodyweight training is the pullup. It is a popular exercise and appears in all kind of workout plans. You will come across pullups in various sports whether it is calisthenics, CrossFit, bodybuilding or power lifting, it is an essential move. Although the pullup is a wanted exercise of many it’s difference is embedded in its form and its variations. A pullup performed in fitness studios and one performed in streetworkout varies significantly, but we will cover proper form in this article.\n\nAt Ykings and in calisthenics the pullup is a basic and essential exercise that qualifies you to learn more advanced movements as well. The effectiveness, its simplicity and applicability inside a home and health clubs but also outside with any object in calisthenics parks is one reason to master this exercise right in the beginning.\n\nAnother reason to learn the pullup is its effectiveness and the muscle groups it targets. You hardly can deny the usefulness of a pullup and its variations if you target a strong back, biceps, latissimus, neck and underarm. If done with perfect form you whole body will be engaged and target also other muscles like your core. Furthermore, it is the perfect counter exercise to push-ups and enables you for many static holds such as the human flag, front and back lever.\n\nQuality form is an absolute must not only for getting respected but also to work muscle memory correctly. Strict and pure pullups like those of calisthenics and gymnastics require a clean range of motion. Bad form can actually have a negative effect on your progress. Work with a spotter early on and perfect the movement.\n\nWhat is a clean pullup?\n\nFirst of all, there are many variations of the pullup and each of them triggers different muscles, however the original clean form of a pullup is what you should start aiming for in the beginning. This means you need to clean it up. Good form is mandatory to get the best out of you and the exercise. A strict and clean pullup is a pullup with an overhand grip on a horizontal bar. Your starting position is the deadhang with extended arms and a retracted shoulder (bringing shoulder blades together). Start pulling up and bring your chin above bar level without using any dynamic movement like swinging your legs. For one rep go slowly back in a deadhang position. One thing to look out for in the beginning is definitely locking out your arms in the deadhang. Even though you just stay there briefly this is of main importance as others would cheat by only going half way and not having the full effect of the pullup movement.\n\nCheck off the following list to perform the pullup correctly.\n<ul>\n	<li>Overhand grip at shoulder width</li>\n	<li>Engaged lower back and core</li>\n	<li>Shoulders back and chest forward</li>\n	<li>Legs straight or bend, but not crossed</li>\n	<li>Controlled movement, no swinging</li>\n	<li>Head over the bar</li>\n	<li>Deadhang (fully locked out arms)</li>\n</ul>\nIn the beginning you most certainly will not have the strength or the patience to perform the pullup in a perfect form. The solution is to progress and evolve to it over time. Aim for clean repetitions and be patient. There is enough to work on early on. With the right progressions and some dedication, you will get there soon.\n\nVariations are not only good to trigger different muscles or fight general boredom with the exercise but also to progress to tougher progressions and other elite movements.\n\nA popular variation of the pullup is the chinup. The main difference here is the grip position and muscle focus. The chinup requires an underhand grip and will also engage your biceps muscle, making them slightly easier in the beginning than the pullup. You can modify and be creative with the pullup and the chinup once you mastered one clean rep. Place your hands either wide and narrow and also play around with over and underhand grips.\n\nGetting started should not be the problem as the earlier progressions suit everyone with any fitness level. Furthermore, you have options to work on your plyometric and explosive power or on your total strength. We will cover all progressions and other exercises in a separate article soon. Take the time and think about where you want to go and which personal needs you want to address.\n\n<strong><em>Using the Ykings smartphone app will not only gradually develop you to master all different progressions, it will also focus on your individual goal of training. The options to go for are:</em></strong>\n<ul>\n	<li><strong><em>Lean – focus on strength development and muscle endurance</em></strong></li>\n	<li><strong><em>Athletic – focus on explosive strength</em></strong></li>\n	<li><strong><em>Strong – focus on maximum strength</em></strong></li>\n</ul>\n<strong><em>Finally, it is essential that you work on your form, gain strength over time and evolve to new movements gradually. Increase your body awareness and flexibility along the way with fully personalized workout plans fitting your needs. Join the community – #WeGrowTogether #StriveForProgress</em></strong>', 'Everything you need to know about a proper pullup', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'everything-you-need-to-know-about-a-proper-pullup', '', '', '2016-04-15 05:38:18', '2016-04-15 05:38:18', '', 0, 'http://ykings.com/?p=1199', 0, 'post', '', 0),
